It is a duty to recover him.”
In all of Bolivia, a land without sea, they still remember vividly the lost coast before Chile in a bloody conflict over resources that took place in the 19th century, as well as the longing to sail the Pacific Ocean again.
Bolivia may be on the verge of a breakthrough, as the International Court of Justice is expected to rule on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
Bolivia has the impulse, a spirit of unity and calm, and of course is waiting for the result with a positive vision,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the failure of the International Court of Justice on large screens spread throughout the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent negotiations, Chile has the obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia sovereignty over the sea.
