“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he said at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will rule in Bolivia's favor and that the situation would change little if it did.
The UN agency based in the Netherlands has no power to adjudicate Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any possible negotiations.
The fact that the resolution of the International Court of Justice comes only six months after the final arguments indicates that the case was not complicated, said Chilean expert Paz Zárate, who specializes in international law.
Far from promoting the cause of Bolivia, the last four years may have hampered it.
