John Edward: linguistic skills are fundamental for citizens of the world
The independent schools in Scotland have a history of excellence in education that has continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional results in the exams that is reinforced by the individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students in all of Scotland, these centers, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS, for its English acronym), are working to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools have as their objective to prepare their students for higher education, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy in the world.
As a sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages are still a popular and desired subject in schools.
As Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, the message goes to his head. If you talk to him in his language, the message goes to his heart."
If you talk to him in his language, you reach his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and generate trust with people from other countries, you can't rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year's exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the tables, with the highest rates of approval in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages got an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centers that make up the SCIS, showed that 72 % of students got an A in Mandarin, while 72 % of students who studied German, 69 % of students who studied French, and 63 % of students who studied Spanish also got an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages because they are seen as a fundamental competitive advantage that children and young people will need in the future without a doubt.
Today, languages are considered to be on the same level as the science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) subjects in the study plans of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey carried out in 2014 by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills revealed that, of the reasons given by employers about difficulties in filling jobs, 17% were attributed to a shortage of linguistic skills.
Therefore, linguistic skills are becoming more and more indispensable for preparing young people for their future careers.
The opportunities for work that require foreign languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career someone chooses, if they learn a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last their whole life.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will give that person an automatic advantage over the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to hold a conversation. It was also established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, the 15%, was French.
This is why investing in language education is important for children today.
If you know several languages, especially those of developing economies, you will be better equipped to find a quality job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on modern classics, while others will teach the most important languages for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools he can choose between several languages taught by specialist teachers.
The independent schools in Scotland devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may hold.
It is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages still have an important role to play in the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages must be considered "languages for international communication."
The independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to the young people of Scotland.
He had to do it.
