North Korea says there is no chance of unilateral disarmament if they don't have confidence
On Saturday, the Foreign Minister of North Korea informed the UN that the continuation of sanctions deepened their distrust of the US and that there was no possibility of their country renouncing their nuclear weapons unilaterally under these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN General Assembly that North Korea had taken "important steps of goodwill" in 2017, including halting nuclear and missile tests and dismantling nuclear test sites, and committing to not proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
However, we have not received any similar response from the United States.
“If we don't have confidence in the United States, we can't have confidence in our national security, and, in those circumstances, there is no possibility of us disarming first unilaterally.”
Although Ri repeated the familiar complaints of North Korea about Washington's resistance to a "phased" denuclearization formula that rewards Pyongyang for taking steps, his statement is important, because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization without preconditions, as North Korea has done in the past.
Ri made reference to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump after the first summit between an active US president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim committed to working toward denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula and Trump guaranteed the security of North Korea.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must renounce its nuclear weapons before it can be considered to have ended the war.
Washington has resisted calls to soften international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States has insisted on nuclear disarmament first and has increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its goal coercively, even objecting to a declaration of the end of the war,” Ri said.
The idea that sanctions can make us fall on our knees is a fantasy of people who don't know us.
The problem is that the continuation of the sanctions deepens our distrust.
Ri did not mention any plans for a second Trump-Kim summit, announced with great fanfare by the US president at the UN General Assembly earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae, the leader of South Korea, in the last five months, and added: "If South Korea had been the interested party in the denuclearization of the peninsula, the denuclearization of the peninsula would not be in such a stalemate."
Even so, Ri's tone was radically different from last year's speech to the UN General Assembly, when he said it was inevitable to direct North Korean missiles toward US soil after Trump called Kim Jong-un "a madman with a nuclear button."
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in moving toward disarmament, but said there was still much to do and that sanctions would have to be maintained until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for this: "We can take two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward North Korea for its advances.
However, as US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The imposition of sanctions by the Security Council must continue energetically and without deviation until we realize a fully verifiable and complete denuclearization."
The UN Security Council has imposed sanctions on North Korea unanimously since 2006, in an attempt to cut off funding for its ballistic missile and nuclear programs.
Pompeo chatted with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and later said he would return to Pyongyang in a month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not good.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that there had been progress, but a few hours later North Korea denounced that its "demands were those of a gangster".
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea agreed to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the US applied the “appropriate measures.”
He said Kim had told him that the measures he was seeking were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and steps toward normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to sleep enough
Thanks to a new course being taught this year at Harvard University, all students are now sleeping more in an attempt to fight the growing culture of studying all night drinking coffee.
A professor discovered that the students at the number one university in the world don't have a clue about basic self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and a specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the US.
His motivation to start the course came after giving a talk on how sleep deprivation affects learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl came up to me and asked why she was just finding out about this now, in her last year.
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of dreams, which surprised me.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts about how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a psychiatry professor at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were sleeping only a few hours a week.
The course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In another section, there is a picture of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on athletic performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to bed.
In another section, participants are told that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
After, an icon of the campus with interactive icons animates the participants to think about their daily routines.
We know that students won't change their behavior immediately.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as anyone has a right to know the effects of smoking tobacco.
He said the culture of pride in staying up all night still exists and added that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping enough and a good quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety; even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation makes the brain generate a feeling of hunger, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying biochemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to expand it to the whole campus.
I hope the next step is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
The professor's recommendation is that students set an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic devices and LED lights, which can alter circadian rhythms, so that they would have problems falling asleep.
