A new cancer vaccine may teach the immune system to "see" cancer cells
A new cancer vaccine may teach the immune system to "see" cancer cells and kill them.
As part of the treatment, the vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize cancer cells.
The method requires extracting immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory.
So, they can "see" a common protein in many cancers and re-inject it.
A vaccine is showing promising results in patients with different cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize cancer cells, saw her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method requires extracting immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory so that they can "see" a common protein called HER2 in many cancers, and then reinjecting the cells.
Jay Berzofsky, a professor at the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results suggest we have a very promising vaccine."
