The only English priest to win a Victoria Cross during the First World War has been honoured in his home town 100 years after his death.
Lieutenant Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann received this decoration on September 29, 1918, in the attack of Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, a sniper killed him four days later and never knew that he had been awarded the highest British military honor.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren discovered a commemorative stone in a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
