According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Saint-Quentin Canal "through a dense fog and under intense fire from machine guns and artillery."
He then ran into the line of fire and, with the "greatest bravery", advanced the line before reaching a cannon with one hand and knocking out three of the detachment.
The lieutenant colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just one month after the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather's actions were "so great that I will never be able to reach his level, but they were very instructive."
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also laid a wreath after the parade, which included the participation of the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said it was an honor for him to be able to take part in the parade and added that "the true heroism of a real hero is shown when he is shown such a strong support."
