The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new investigation, which has been carried out in the Highlands of Scotland, is trying to discover how bats use the landscape to find food.
It is expected that what is discovered will shed more light on the behaviour of the only flying mammals and help to guide future conservation activities.
The study, carried out by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and soprano bats, as well as the brown long-eared bat and Daubenton's bat of the gardens of Inverewe in Wester Ross.
They will place special recording devices in strategic locations on the property to track the bats' activities during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile investigations with portable detectors.
Experts will analyse the sounds picked up on the recordings to discover the frequency of calls from the bats and what species make them.
Then a report and a habitat map will be produced to create a detailed image of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation advisor for NTS, is hoping the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
With this information, the benefits of habitat management will be determined, such as the creation of meadows and how to maintain forests for bats and other associated species.
The populations of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from the construction and development that affects their nests and the loss of their habitat.
The wind turbines and the electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticides and other chemical treatments of construction materials or attacks by domestic cats.
The bats are not really blind.
But, due to his nocturnal hunting habits, his ears are more useful than his eyes in achieving his goal.
They use a sophisticated technique of ecolocalization that locates ants and obstacles on their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historical buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes the issue of bats very seriously.
He has ten experts trained in the matter, who carry out regular surveys, inspections of nests and, in some cases, rescues.
The organization has opened the first and only bat reserve in Scotland in the state of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, which is the home of eight of the ten species of bat in Scotland.
The property's director, David Thompson, says it's the ideal territory for them.
“Here, in Threave, we have a fantastic area for bats,” he said.
We have old buildings, many old trees and the right habitat.
However, there are still many unknowns about bats, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand better what they need to develop.
It is important to check for bats before doing maintenance work inside the properties, as you could destroy a breeding colony accidentally and kill 400 females and young, which would mean wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy their colonies.
The Scottish official of the Bat Conservation Trust, Elisabeth Ferrell, has urged the public to help.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species about which we don't know how their populations evolve."
