Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team has won the Ryder Cup of 2018 by defeating the American team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National, outside Paris (France).
The United States has now lost six consecutive matches on European soil since its last victory in the Ryder Cup in 1993.
Europe reclaimed the Ryder Cup when the Danish captain Thomas Bjorn's team won 14.5 points to beat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who had to fight hard for most of the tournament, admitted defeat on the 16th hole, a par 3, conceding his defeat to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari stood out in all his rounds, becoming one of the four players to ever achieve a 5-0-0 in the current format of the tournament since it began in 1979.
Jordan Spieth lost to the lowest-ranked player on the European team, Denmark's Thorbjorn Olesen, 5 and 4.
The world's number one player, Dustin Johnson, fell 2 and 1 to the Englishman Ian Poulter, who could have played his last Ryder Cup.
The Spanish Sergio García, a veteran who has already won eight Ryder Cups, became the European player with the most victories in the history of the tournament with 25.5 points in his career.
