Red tide update: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission) shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which suggests a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide bloom extends approximately 130 miles along the Florida coast from Pinellas County to Lee County.
There are irregular parcels as far as 10 miles from the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer than last week.
There is also a red tide in Pasco County.
During the past week, there have been medium-sized concentrations in the County of Pinellas and on its coast, medium-sized concentrations between low and high in the County of Hillsborough, medium-sized concentrations of low to high in the County of Manatee, medium-sized concentrations of low to high in the County of Sarasota and its coast, medium-sized concentrations of low to high in the County of Charlotte, medium-sized concentrations of low to high in the County of Lee and on its coast, and low concentrations in the County of Collier.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwest part of Florida during the past week.
